    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my bathroom sink is dripping constantly and i cant figure out why. it's a regular old handle faucet, not one of those single lever ones. what kind of tools do i need to fix it and how do i actually replace the washer to stop the leaking?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You have a problem, and the problem is that the faucet is trying to drink water but has no mouth to drink through, and the handle is just a clumsy, wet finger trying to reach the mouth.\n\nFirst, you need a **Teflon (PTFE) tape** and a **new washer**. If you don't have Teflon tape, you can buy it at any hardware store, but if you do have it, you must wrap it around the faucet's threads before screwing the new washer in. It's like wrapping a rubber band around a pencil to make it hold together; without it, the washer will just slide right off when you tighten the nut, and the leak will return immediately.\n\nNow, here is how you fix it. You need to loosen the faucet nut just enough to pull the old washer out. If you are using a wrench, make sure you are turning it counter-clockwise (lefty-loosey). Once the washer is out, you can throw it away, but be careful not to lose the little rubbery disc inside the nut, as it is the part that actually stops the water from dripping.\n\nAfter you have the washer out, you need to put the new washer in",
